ation and trafficking. The major areas of intervention within the range of the NPA are: Prevention, Protection, Recovery and Reintegration, Perpetrators, Child Participation, HIV/AIDS, STIs and Substance Abuse, Co-ordination and Monitoring A National Monitoring and Implementation Committee on National Plan of Action against Sexual Exploitation and Abuse of Children including Trafficking (SEACT) has been formed to implement the National Plan of Action Allows for d etention of women under 18 years of age if", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7dee12b9-5a70-4705-b406-77aef233ce63": {"__data__": {"id_": "7dee12b9-5a70-4705-b406-77aef233ce63", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/men-and-prevention-gender-based-violence", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "Men and the Prevention of Gender based Violence", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/men-and-prevention-gender-based-violence", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "16f387ecadf8c12d98b65a061de0b55129255bf882209a1913a9b27f681fc509"}}, "hash": "16f387ecadf8c12d98b65a061de0b55129255bf882209a1913a9b27f681fc509", "text": "found in a place where prostitution is being carried out. The Cruelty to Women (Deterrent Punishment) Ordinance 1983 amends relevant section of the Penal Code and provides the penalty of life imprisonment for kidnapping, abduction, trafficking in women, cruelty because of dowry, and rape as well as abetment of such offenses. India Prevention of Immoral Traffic Act of 1986 (PITA) Nepal Human Trafficking (Control) Act (July 2007) - Prohibition against engaging in human trafficking and operating a brothel - Outlines punishment for traffickers - Rehabilitation fund and centre established - Establishes a Committee on Human Trafficking Control to work on controling trafficking, supporting rehabilition work and coordinating activities of organisations working on human trafficking Sri Lanka Penal Code Amendment Act (2006) Strengthened provisions against trafficking, sexual abuse of children, child pornography, child prostitution and child trafficking. It also criminalizes recruiting of child soldiers. Pakistan Prevention and Control of Human Trafficking Ordinance, 2002 Human trafficking is punishable with imprisonment, which may extend to ten years and shall also be liable to fine. The Ordinance also provides for punishment for imprisonment, which may extends to seven years and shall also be liable to fine for the planning of human trafficking. Acid Control Laws Banglades h Acid Crime Control Act and Acid Control Act (2002) The Acid Control Act seeks to control the sale, production and use of acid and provides acid victims treatment, rehabilitation and legal assistance. The Acid Crime Control Act institutes harsh penalties for acid violence through large fines, 3 years to life prison sentences and death penalty. It should be noted that while acid attacks have decreased, the harsh penalties have also meant that judges are reluctant to implement them. Dowry Prohibition Laws India Dowry Prohibition Act (1961) Indian Penal Code Section 498A (Cruelty) \u2013 1983 Indian Penal Code Section 304B (Dowry Death) - 1986 The Dowry Prohibition Act criminalizes giving, taking, demanding and helping the giving, taking or demanding of dowry IPC 498A institutes punishment for the cruelty and harassment by the husband or family which includes demanding of dowry. IPC 304B - If a woman death can be attributed to cruelty or harassment by the husband or his family relating to a deman for dowry, then the death of a woman is considered to be a dowry death and the person committing the death is punishable by 7year to life imprisonment. Nepal Social Customs and Practices Act Prohibiting the dowry system Banglades h Dowry Prohibition Act (1980) Penalties in place for giving, taking and demanding dowry 41 Female Infanticide India The Pre- conception and Pre-natal Diagnostic Techniques (Prohibition of Sex Selection) Act, 1994. \u201cAn Act to provide for the regulation of the use of pre-natal diagnostic techniques for the purpose of detecting genetic or metabolic disorders or chromosomal abnormalities or certain congenital malformations or sex linked disorders and for the prevention of the misuse of such techniques for the purpose of pre-natal sex determination leading to female foeticide; and, for matters connected there with or incidental thereto.\u201d http://mohfw.nic.in/THE%20PNDT%20ACT%20(PRINCIPAL%20ACT)1994. htm", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bd5b0d7b-65a8-454e-a59e-54712a097926": {"__data__": {"id_": "bd5b0d7b-65a8-454e-a59e-54712a097926", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "3dd6bcc954be842e32d7686b6d63befb1f54ce414dea9e1bd1e01608a500c6b1"}, "3": {"node_id": "8651ad36-16a2-4593-b80b-27c8f486e7fd", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "10253a8d9e0b1644d041058b7746cfad6266ed507425f2762788aa21d4eba733"}}, "hash": "474e159d7afec7537525fc14f305ea81a519ddda708ce50f10714f0dc997f068", "text": "Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia National Climate Funds, jointly pepared by UNDP and Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia-Pacific region on the design and management of , jointly pepared by UNDP and the BTFEC. Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Pacific region on the design and management of 2 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation Table of Contents Introduction ................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 3 The design of the BTFEC at a Glance .................................................................................................................................................................................................. 4 The role of the BTFEC in financing environmental conservation in Bhutan ................................................................................................................. 4 The legal status ...................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 4 The model: different types of funds .............................................................................................................................................................................................. 5 Governing body and beneficiaries ................................................................................................................................................................................................ 6 Fiduciary standards .............................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 7 The establishment process of the BTFEC ......................................................................................................................................................................................... 7 The management of the BTFEC ........................................................................................................................................................................................................... 8 Granting Program................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 8 The monitoring and evaluation ...................................................................................................................................................................................................... 9 Resource Mobilization ........................................................................................................................................................................................................................ 9 Lessons-learned ....................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 10 Managing financial risks related to the endowment fund ................................................................................................................................................. 10 Becominga fully Bhutanese managed Trust Fund ................................................................................................................................................................ 10 The granting mechanism guided by a five year strategic plan ........................................................................................................................................ 11 3 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation Introduction This paper aims to enrich knowledge sharing aboutthe establishment and management of national climate funds (NCFs), which is organized by the Asia-Pacific Community of Practice on Climate Finance. To provide a technical input to the knowledge sharing, UNDP commissioned seven case studies on existing national funds in the fields of environment, conservation, energy, climate change and development. Thispaper reports the lessons learned extracted from the establishment and management of the Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation (BTFEC), which is one of seven national funds across the Asia-Pacific region selected as acase study.1 The BTFEC is selected to provide an interesting case for countries in Asia-Pacific because of the following characteristics: 1. The ability to manage a full-scale endowment fund.In 2011, the total investment managed by the BTFEC was US$ 42.3 million, which was growing from US$ 21 millionwhen it was first established in 1992. The fund, whichis currently invested in the capital market both in the US as well as in Bhutan, generates interests or dividendsto provide grants for eligible environmental conservation projects in Bhutan. In FY 2011, the total revenue (from both dividend/interest and net capital gain) generated from the endowment fund was US$ 2.2 million. 2. The transformation of the BTFEC to be fully Bhutanese. In 2001, the high-level management board became fully Bhutanese. During the initiation of the BTFEC, the fund was a collaborative venture between the Royal Government of Bhutan, United Nations Development Program (UNDP), and World Wildlife Fund (WWF). While WWF obtained a seat in the management board, UNDP served as an ex-officio member without a voting power. The transition process to be fully Bhutanese in the management board took five years. As of today, the asset management committee and the secretariat of the BTFEC are also managed entirely by Bhutanese individuals. 3. The granting mechanism guided by five-year frameworks of strategic funding priorities. Grants are awarded to eligible Bhutanese individuals and institutions based on the program focuses set in the five-year strategic frameworks. This approach ensures a more targeted granting program to achieve the environmental conservationobjectives of Bhutan. This report first summarizes the design of the BTFEC and provides ashort description about the establishment and the management of the BTFEC.The lessons-learned from the establishment and management of the BTFEC are then presented.The case study analysis involved: literature review to set the scope of the study and in-depth interviews with relevant stakeholders: 1) the Fund Manager and Staff from the BTFEC, 2) board members: the Minister of Agriculture and Forests and RSPN, and 3) beneficiaries: National Environment Commission and Tarayana Foundation. Prior to finalization, the report has been reviewed by the BTFEC team and the UNDP Bhutan Country Office.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n