nded by the fund for the promotion of social welfare through environmental conservation in Bhutan. The Charter also mandates the Government to maintain Bhutan\u2019s forest cover at 60 percent of the country\u2019s area as the protected areas. The rules and regulations governing the day-to-day operations of the fund are detailed in the Operation Manual issued in 2009. Although established by a government regulation, the BTFEC is considered as an independent grant maker guided by strategic funding framework. Five out of six members sitting in the Management Board are representative from the government with one member from civil society. The Director and the secretariat staff are non civil service positions. 2Namgyal, ST, 2001, Future Directions for the Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation, Journal of Bhutan Studies, Vol. 3, No. 1. 3Ditto 4 The grant making was also rather limited because of lack of proposal writing capacity and also BTFEC was a new establishment and during that period the Secretariat was in process of developing its first five-year strategic plan. 5 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation The model: different types of funds The BTFEC currently manages an endowment fund, where the principal capital is kept in perpetuity and not consumed, while only the income from the investment is used to provide grants. An endowment fund appears to be quite useful for small and aid-dependence countries to ensure a sustainable financing mechanism to contribute in providing a certain public service. During the establishment of the BTFEC, donationsof in total US$21 millionwere raised. The main donors included the Global Environment Facility, Denmark, Finland, the Netherlands, Norway and Switzerland.As of the first quarter of 2011, the trust fund\u2019s asset was US$44.0 million (with the total endowment fund of US$ 42.3 million). This increase is possible because the incomes generated from the endowment were reinvested back to add up to the endowment fund. The total annual income from interests and dividend in 2008-2009 and 2009-2010 were US$ 418,211 and US$ 625,927 respectively. In 2010-2011, the net capital gain reached US$ 1.4 million. Table 1 shows the fluctuation of the total revenues received from interest/dividends and also from capital gain of equities. Table 1.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "bbb8e839-d245-42c1-8931-2e1024ca5105": {"__data__": {"id_": "bbb8e839-d245-42c1-8931-2e1024ca5105", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "325bb50385e294ff4eeb7f534a58931b6aa0ddaa909ddbe40dfd59c147d25f7a"}, "2": {"node_id": "699f11ea-bc3e-4ac6-b657-30f174acb3b4", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f54e3b2dd082802f08fab4d5f76bbce811aadced5cb3794c9f16834a64e4399e"}}, "hash": "275680594b7b91cb0a0287d7f6bbdded828e0cd1568733bf2afa9ee634af00fe", "text": "Table 1. BTEF Portfolio (US$) Year Total Assets Revenues Granting 2005-2006 30,573,442 1,744,766 122,229 2006-2007 32,653,378 2,552,994 225,613 2007-2008 41,294,958 7,754,174 195,814 2008-2009 41,190,041 418,211 155,498 2009-2010 40,945,230 625,927 369,721 2010-2011 42,299,560 2,278,265 813,459 Source: BTFEC annual report 2005-2011 The Royal Charter 1996 fully entrusts the Board with the fiduciary mandate over the Trust Fund\u2019s financial endowment. The Board should adopt appropriate investment policies, regulations, as well as guidelines and delegate investment authority and responsibilities to the Asset Management Committee (AMC) for general investment matters and to the Secretariat for investment operations. A guideline containing of investment policies has been developed to determine the investment portfolio (i.e. how much the endowment fund should be put in stocks and/or bonds). The guideline, which is approved by the board, provides a basis for the AMC to make decisions on the investments. Currently the Finance Officer of the", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "397bcb29-07ee-42f8-8100-e757d1b090cb": {"__data__": {"id_": "397bcb29-07ee-42f8-8100-e757d1b090cb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4a74b44c8c86385e547a86eb92cb06e85e36fa13febc2f1e4cb33ae4543ca98b"}, "3": {"node_id": "83aec1ca-b1a1-4651-a546-21911edb16d3", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c8df50b3de76a0fbade5c5e7cdda64e747cc79446cfad2dc0f09de5d53bef954"}}, "hash": "d152f27275b551be47b17130a0b19e2ff535c5dde5b40f9128d5797635a69909", "text": "BTFEC monitors the investments of the endowment fund on a daily basis from Bhutan. The BTFEC considers their existing investment portfolio as quite risky.The entire trust fund endowment is invested in a mixed portfolio of global and U.S. equities and fixed income instruments.Equity investments are permitted to equal as much as 70 percent of the market value of the total assets under management, whilefixed-income investments (corporate and government bonds) shall equal at least 30 percent of the total assets\u2019 market value.To mitigate the risks, the BTFEC constantly monitors the US financial market and spreads the stocks out thinly. Several guidelines regulate the investment policies include for instance: 1) equity investments shall be concentrated in dividend-paying corporations; and 2)quality of fixed-income investments shall be maintained at a level of at least Moody\u2019s top two ratings or the equivalent rating by another agency.5Furthermore, investments should be made in corporations whose activities generally are in line with the conservation philosophy of the trust fund. The BTFEC considers itself as a socially responsible 5 Moody's Investors Service provides international financial research on bonds issued by commercial and government entities: http://www.moodys.com 6 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation investor, where the trust fund regularly reviews its holdings to screen out any individual holdings in the portfolio that appear to represent poor environmental performers. The BTFEC has started to bring part of the endowment fund back to Bhutan to be invested in the country itself. Investments in Bhutan currently provide a greater potential to generate higher interests compared to investments in developed countries. Initially the BTFEC brought back US$ 1 million. Now, the investment within the country has reached US$ 6 million, which is invested in three commercial banks, one insurance company and one trading company. Governing body and beneficiaries The governing structure of the BTFEC consists of a Management Board, a secretariat led by a director, and an Asset Management Committee, with the following roles and responsibilities: 1. A Management Board, consisting of six members, has all powers of the management of the Trust Fund. The members of the board consist of: the Minister of Agriculture and Forests as the Chairman of the Board, the Secretary of National Environmental Commission, the Director of National Budget, the Head of Policy and Planning of the Ministry of Works and Human Settlement, the Executive Director of Royal society for Protection of Nature (a local NGO), the Director of Cabinet Secretariat, and finally the Director of the BTFEC as the ex-officio Member Secretary of the Board. The Board will select the Chairman from among the members of the government and shall appoint the Director and the Investment Managers to manage the investments based on the investment guidelines. At present, the Asset Management Committee (AMC) functions as an Investment Manager, although the BTFEC can have an Investment Manager in addition to the AMC. 2. A Director carries out the day-to-day management of the BTFEC in accordance with the powers and duties established by the Board. The Director will be the Chief Executive Officer of the Fund and will directly report to the Management Board. The Director will implement the Board\u2019s decisions and oversee the day-to-day activities of the Fund. The Director will be supported by a full time secretariat 3. An Asset Management Committeeconsists of the Ministry of Finance, Druk Holdings and Investments (DHI), National Pension Funds, Royal Monetary Authority, and an individual consultant from the US. The committee has investment authority and responsibilities for general investment matters. Government agencies, local not-for-profit non-government organizations, grassroots communities and qualified Bhutanese individuals are eligible to receive financial support from the BTFEC. Annually, the BTFEC has approximately US$ 1.5 million to give away as grants, which can be accessed through two funding windows: large scale projects with a ceiling up to Nu. 13 million (or $300,000) and discretionary grants with ceiling up to Nu. 400,000 (or $10,000). While the discretionary grants are awarded on rolling basis, all large- scale grants have to follow the funding cycle, where the deadlines for proposal submissions are on 31 May and 31 December. To make decision on the technical soundness and financial aptness of project proposals, the BTFEC has the Technical Advisory Panel (TAP) that consists of representatives from different sectors.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "83aec1ca-b1a1-4651-a546-21911edb16d3": {"__data__": {"id_": "83aec1ca-b1a1-4651-a546-21911edb16d3", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4a74b44c8c86385e547a86eb92cb06e85e36fa13febc2f1e4cb33ae4543ca98b"}, "2": {"node_id": "397bcb29-07ee-42f8-8100-e757d1b090cb", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "d152f27275b551be47b17130a0b19e2ff535c5dde5b40f9128d5797635a69909"}}, "hash": "c8df50b3de76a0fbade5c5e7cdda64e747cc79446cfad2dc0f09de5d53bef954", "text": "The proposal review process by the TAP usually takes about one to two months (depending on the number of proposals for review). The TAP will then provide recommendations to the Board whether a proposal can be awarded or declined funding. Considering the recommendations provided by the TAP, the Management Board, who meets in September and April every year, will then make", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d3c9e812-9840-475a-aaab-a478a523f092": {"__data__": {"id_": "d3c9e812-9840-475a-aaab-a478a523f092", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "8337bb5542f746ba06e69fa0bd45a3510773b6f86b158f8adfdc18f9c51851a1"}}, "hash": "8337bb5542f746ba06e69fa0bd45a3510773b6f86b158f8adfdc18f9c51851a1", "text": "the final decision on the grant projects. 7 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation Fiduciary standards The fiduciary standard included in the Charter and the Operations Manual cover the following aspects: - Financial management and integrity - the manual stipulates that: \u2022 accounting of the Fund and preparation of consolidated financial statements shall be based on the Generally Accepted Accounting principles; \u2022 the budget and the budgeting system shall encompass a clear link between receipts, expenditure and objectives and shall be continuously managed and monitored; \u2022 all Revenue and Expenditure shall be recognized on accrual basis (revenue and expenses are incurred but not realized at the time of reporting). - Procurement - the manual stipulates the procurement procedure, which shall be aimed at promoting an open and effective purchasing policy and the effective and efficient use of Fund\u2019s money. - Financial mismanagement \u2013 the following procedure dealing with financial mismanagement is included in the manual (p. 32): \u2022 If it transpires during investigations that an act of fraud, negligence or financial irregularity could be perpetrated because of some defect in the rules and procedures, the director shall take immediate remedial action to rectify the shortcomings, and the Board informed in writing immediately; \u2022 Every effort shall be made to recover the whole amount of loss from the persons found guilty, especially when cause of the loss was commitment of willful fraud or financial irregularity. If it is found that laxity of supervision facilitated the fraud, the supervising officer at fault shall also be penalized. \u2022 On completion of investigations in a reported case of loss, the Treasurer/director shall issue a sanction order for affecting the write off and/or consequent recovery of cost, if any. If the amount of loss in cash or stock is replenished immediately on reporting or on completion of investigations, no write off shall be effected. - Audit \u2013 the Royal Charter has also mandated internal audit, which should be conducted by qualified auditors recognized by the Board. The annual audit is usually conducted by a qualified auditor of the Royal Audit Authority of Bhutan. The findings of the audit are made public on request, while the audited financial reports are uploaded in the BTFEC website. Finally, the Director prepares financial statement and work progress reports of the Trust Fund every year within six months of the end of the financial year and submit to the Board and distribute to donors upon review and approval of the Board. The establishment process of the BTFEC The BTFEC was created for sustainable financing for conservation under the leadership of farsighted monarch, his Majesty the Fourth King of Bhutan. It was first established in 1991 as a joint collaboration between the Royal Government of Bhutan, WWF-US and the UNDP. The driving force behind the establishment of BTFEC was the state policy to maintain 60 percent of the total land in Bhutan for conservation for all times to come and to ensure operationalization of all protected areas. Setting up an endowment fund was expected to ensure sustainable financing of conservation. At the time of the establishment, there was a trend of establishing an endowment fund for conservation worldwide. The establishment of BTFEC was made possible because of strong political will, institutional support and the wise leadership. 8 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation Due to a strong political push from the government, there were no significant transaction costs identified during the establishment of the BTFEC. The BTFEC staff recalled that the political process during the establishment of the fund was rather smooth and swift. It was however pointed out that the BTFEC had to pay management fees to UNDP as the fund manager soon after the establishment of the fund. Assistance was required at the beginning of the management of the BTFEC since the trust fund office was only started with a very small team consisting of a director and very limited staff.However, the management fees paid to UNDP as the fund manager was considered costly. Between 1993 and 1996, there was limited spending (grants provided to beneficiaries) but the focus was mainly on increasing the capacity, strengthening its institution and the capital for the endowment fund. The scaling up of the BTFEC granting programs only occurred after ten years of the implementation. This decision has actually contributed to building the capacity of the BTFEC and the government prior to providing grants to beneficiaries. The management of the BTFEC Granting Program As of 2011, the trust fund has generated $29.30 million of revenue and provided grants to 109 individuals and institutions. The grant-", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f1421f67-e7d5-4c71-afad-fccb5a422642": {"__data__": {"id_": "f1421f67-e7d5-4c71-afad-fccb5a422642", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6dafa15b4ec101be7bb581df0edb7a5b427ea14415999ecf008f8890298eb076"}}, "hash": "6dafa15b4ec101be7bb581df0edb7a5b427ea14415999ecf008f8890298eb076", "text": "making program under the trust fund is guided by the BTFEC five-year strategic plan. The frameworks are formulated through consultation processes and translated into the trust fund's five-year strategic plan.The Second Strategic Plan of 2011-2015 has the following program focuses: research, economic development with direct impacts on natural environment, climate change adaptation strategies, awareness and education, green sector proposals and rural community projects as well as integrated water resources management (IWRM). The BTFEC works closely with grant seekers and facilitatesthe preparation of grant proposals. Grant seekers are advised to write a brief letter of inquiryto determine if the fund presents interests and permits consideration of request. The letter should include: purpose, problems to be addressed, information about organization, budget and duration estimation, and contact information. After receiving the letter, the BTFEC may ask the grant seeker to submit a formal proposal, which must address one of the fund\u2019s strategic funding objectives. During eachcall for proposal, around 8-15 proposals are received andusually only 5-6 proposals are approved (mainly from government agencies). The quality of the proposals is often not technical and financially sound, even those received from government agencies, while very limited proposals are received from local communities. The BTFEC has attempted to encourage local NGOs and community groups to submit proposals by providing training and simplifying the application procedure. To ensure grants are reaching the targeted beneficiaries particularly at the local level, two types of granting mechanisms are implemented: - Grant applicants from government (or established) institutions, which usually propose for larger and complex projects. For these applications, a higher standard in the screening process is applied. - While for local communities, a lower (simplified) standard is applied in screening the projects, where intervention from the fund management is required to provide support to project proponents. Proposals received directly from grassroots communities are preferred. When submitted by government and NGOs, proposals that enhance community involvement in conservation will be prioritized. Co-financing is desired, but the fund its support should not replace other donor funding. The maximum size of individual grants is Nu. 13 million (US$ 300,000), and individual grants can have a maximum duration of three years. Discretionary small grants not exceeding Nu. 400,000 (approximately US$ 10,000) per grant are also 9 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation available. The BTFEC can provide up to six small grants operational at one time or a maximum total budget of Nu.2.4 million per annum. The monitoring and evaluation The BTFEC implements both technical and financial monitoring. The financial monitoring includes scrutinizing the disbursement and the utility of the finances of the projects, while the technical monitoring require the assessment of impacts of the projects. Grantees should submit progress reports, both financial and technical, on a quarterly and semi-annual to the BTFEC followed by yearly comprehensive technical and financial report at the end of the fiscal year. At the end of the fiscal year, grantees should also submit financial and technical reports to the BTFEC. The Trust Fund carries out regular supervision through field visits. The Secretariat keeps the Board informed on the progress of its activities through quarterly and half-yearly progress reports. At the end of fiscal year the BTFEC will put into the public domain an annual report covering technical progress and consolidated audited financial statements. Each grant will be evaluated through mid-term evaluation and implementation completion reporting and the results will be published. The BTFEC realizes that there is room for improvement particularly related to the monitoring and evaluation of projects. Currently, the BTFEC can only measure the results of project implementation through written reports provided every quarter by project implementers. A completion report, which is required at the end of a project, also provides information related to both the finances and the results of the projects. The existing monitoring system relies mainly on the written reports submitted by project implementers. Only when the management suspects any irregularity or violation, an officer will then clarify and verify the matter on the ground. This monitoring system is regarded as not ideal as it relies only on written reports, yet it is the most reasonable system since currently the BTFEC manages around 25 projects during a year. Resource Mobilization The growing of the endowment fund over time was possible due to the decisions made to initially reinvest the dividends and interests generated to add up the endowment fund. The BTFEC applies a fixed annual spending ceiling that outlines both an operational spending target and a portion of annual revenues to be reinvested to increase the capital base. The latter is particularly essential since the trust fund has", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "19eb9dd6-6ce8-47a0-bc47-144c11252343": {"__data__": {"id_": "19eb9dd6-6ce8-47a0-bc47-144c11252343", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "84523e068979049f59279a07c128487e309a1d94c2773e70966917a625028dd3"}}, "hash": "84523e068979049f59279a07c128487e309a1d94c2773e70966917a625028dd3", "text": "not pursued any major fundraising since it became fully operational with $21 million in 1996.The preliminary estimates indicate that the trust fund endowment would need more than $50 million before its revenues could feasibly maintain a public grant-making window for environmental conservation in Bhutan.6However, with the current situation in the world of financial investments, there is no guarantee for performance related to the rates of return. The BTFEC is now seeking the opportunities of involving local industries and Bhutanese people in resource mobilization. The BTFEC is currently also accessing a World BankGEF project (US$ 4.08 million) for the northern area of Bhutan. A series of fund raising events are conducted and a fundraising expert has been hired. 6Namgyal, ST, 2001, Future Directions for the Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation, Journal of Bhutan Studies, Vol. 3, No. 1. 10 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation Lessons-learned Managing financial risks related to the endowment fund The BTFEC has been very aggressive in pursuing its investment portfolio. Yet it has been very prudent in mitigating the financial risks of its investment. Capital markets are the most unpredictable avenues of investment, with high uncertainty involved related to the amount of revenues that will be generated. The investment manager is expected to play a crucial role to ensure steady revenues for future strategic plans and reinvestment into the endowment. However, the BTFEC exposure to global equities (currently permitted up to 70 percent of the portfolio) could possibly be an area of concern, although fund management's credible risk diversification strategies.7 Several strategies that can be applied to mitigate the financial risks of the endowment fund are: 1. Theoretically, investors should identify their tolerance for market risk and then build a portfolio of different investment holdings that maximizes the expected rate of return given that level of risk (i.e., diversification). Investors can then decide on how much and where to allocate resources in order to maximize returns. Obviously every investment, whether private or public, carries different size, timing, and risk characteristics that must be taken into consideration. 2. The BTFEC focuses mainly on the consistency of the total return of the endowment fund over an extended period of time rather than the fluctuating returns that may occur over shorter interim periods. To achieve this objective, it is crucial to have a prudent manager with professional skills in investments as the investment manager. 3. To remain competitive, the trust fund is also regularizing periodic and independent evaluations of the performance of both the investment portfolio and its fund manager. Becominga fully Bhutanese managed Trust Fund Similar to many national funds that are established with external support, the BTFEC was initially managed by an international agency. The intention to move to be a fully Bhutanese trust fund has been mentioned and instructed by the Royal Charter.As stipulated by the Charter, all six members of the Management Board should be representatives from revelant agencies in Bhutan after five years of the issuance of the Charter in 1996. This transformation was also followed by the nationalization of the Asset Management Committee. In 1996, the trust fund's board contracted investment management to a professional investment manager based in the United States, while UNDP was serving as a fund manager. After around 6-7 years, the BTFEC decided to manage the fund by itself to reduce overhead costs and low performance of the manager in question and was replaced by individual investment advisor. This arrangement lasted for another 5-6 years, when the BTFEC then decided to establish its own Asset Management Committee (AMC), consisting of Bhutanese individuals from relevant institutions and an individual from the US. The BTFEC has been successful in moving towards to be a fully Bhutanese trust fund. The process has been gradual. Particularly for the Management Board, it became fully Bhutanese in 2001, which was 5 years after the implementation of the Charter or almost 9 years after the establishment of the BTFEC.The transformation process can only be made possible due to the following enabling situations: 1. Capacity \u2013 the increase of capacity obviously is one of the success factors enabling the transformation to a fully Bhutanese trust fund. In the first ten years of the establishment, the BTFEC has focused mainly on building the capacity, strengthening the 7Ditto 11 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation institution and increasing the total endowment fund. Once the capacity is ready, the BTFEC then moved to strengthen its granting portfolio. The decision to strengthen its capacity during the first ten years has been proven fruitful as the BTFEC has now become a strong national", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "8c62c21a-d806-41eb-a416-d8ede5a8b6f7": {"__data__": {"id_": "8c62c21a-d806-41eb-a416-d8ede5a8b6f7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-bhutan-trust-fund-environmental-conservation", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "937acf7c54bd3e719503aa0ccca98557ec9f12d34d027b04330482ddd1c813d9"}}, "hash": "937acf7c54bd3e719503aa0ccca98557ec9f12d34d027b04330482ddd1c813d9", "text": "institution with grant-making capacity to support biodiversity conservation in Bhutan. 2. Political will and minimizing cost\u2013 Although the process of moving to be a fully Bhutanese trust fund took place gradually, the transformation itself (particularly for the nationalization of the Management Board) has been instructed by the Royal Charter. The transformation of the AMC to be fully Bhutanese also occurred following the assessments conducted related to the costs of hiring international fund manager and investment managers. The main driver of the transformation of the AMC was mainly to minimize the management costs of the BTFEC. The granting mechanism guided by a five year strategic plan The BTFEC annual grant making has been guided by five-years strategic plans. The strategic plans of the BTFEC are formulated to coincide with the government development plan. The strategic plans in five-year cycles present a cohesive well-grounded funding strategy to ensure the most effective utilization of trust fund resources. They also serve as an excellent indicator of efficient strategic planning,which allows for a more transparent process of project selection and, most importantly, ensures that the fund contributes to the achievement of environmental conservation in the country. Having the granting program guided by the strategic plans prevents the overlap between projects particularly those funded by government and those supported by external support. Strategic plans guiding the BTFEC granting program have also provided a room for measuring impacts of the Trust Fund. The BTFEC can include measurable targets and goals to be achieved within a period of time in the strategic plans. Having these quantifiedtargets will allow for a concrete impact evaluation framework to be put in place to assess the impact of its grants. The monitoring and evaluation of the BTFEC can also move towards establishing key performance indicators of each projects to have quantitative criteria to assess the performance of grant projects and to base future interventions. 12 Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation Authors: Silvia Irawan, Pema Choenphyel, Chukey Wangchuk, Singye Dorji, Alex Heikens Cover Photo: Department of Tourism (Tourism Council of Bhutan) Acknowledgements: the authors would like to express their gratitude to representatives from government, development partners and grantees of the fund sharing their views and experiences with the Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation. Disclaimer: The views expressed in this publication are those of the authors and do not necessarily represent those of the United Nations, including UNDP, or its member states. Citation: Irawan et al. (2012) Case Study Report: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation. A UNDP/BTFEC working paper. http://www.snap-undp.org/elibrary/default.aspx", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "af006a27-30a9-4a3e-91cd-53b2a6d1cb9c": {"__data__": {"id_": "af006a27-30a9-4a3e-91cd-53b2a6d1cb9c", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "26643c361d6269cc27bc49538021a336558f7fa57f47d79c58e011d761827218"}, "3": {"node_id": "7eb89ae0-bb85-4649-9631-ade44900b6d7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ba0818363c1d86de579a7746901c409e1396611c0f810364b47efa1aad36adb2"}}, "hash": "90266d4a99df73d9d695d9a3579cda9932022ab8cef963451ea65fcbc8bd9c8a", "text": "Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia National Climate Funds, jointly pepared by UNDP and Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia-Pacific region on the design and management of , jointly pepared by UNDP and the CCCA trust fund. Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund Pacific region on the design and management of 2 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund Table of Contents Introduction ................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 3 The design of the CCCA Trust Fund at a glance ............................................................................................................................................................................ 3 The legal status ...................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 3 The model of the CCCA Trust Fund .................................................................................................................................................................................................... 4 Governing body and beneficiaries ................................................................................................................................................................................................ 5 The Management of the CCCA Trust Fund ...................................................................................................................................................................................... 6 Project Cycle ........................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 6 Monitoring and Evaluation ............................................................................................................................................................................................................... 7 Lessons learned .......................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 7 3 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund Introduction This paper aims to enrich knowledge sharing about the establishment and management of national climate funds (NCFs), which is organized by the Asia-Pacific Community of Practice on Climate Finance. To provide a technical input to the knowledge sharing, UNDP commissioned seven case studies on existing national funds in the fields of environment, conservation, energy, climate change and development. This paper reports the lessons learned extracted from the establishment and management of the Cambodia Climate Change Alliance (CCCA) Trust Fund, which is one of seven national funds across the Asia-Pacific region selected as a case study.1 This report provides the summary of the overall design of the CCCA Trust Fund and a short description about the process of the establishment and the management of the CCCA Trust Fund. A brief analysis of the lessons-learned from the establishment and management of the CCCA Trust Fund are then presented. A desk review was conducted to examine documents related to the CCCA Trust Fund. The Secretariat of the CCCA Trust Fund, Dr. Tin Ponlok, also provided inputs to the paper. The design of the CCCA Trust Fund at a glance In 2006, the government of Cambodia established the National Climate Change Committee (NCCC), consisting of 20 ministries and agencies as a coordinating and policy support entity for all aspects of climate change. To strengthen the capacity of the NCCC and to enable line ministries and CSOs to implement priority climate change actions, the CCCA program was established in 2010. The CCCA aims to support the development of technical and institutional capacity at national and sub-national levels to address current and future climate related challenges. One of the efforts pursued by the CCCA is securing external funding for selected priority interventions through a multi-donor CCCA Trust Fund. The CCCA includes a unified engagement point for development partners and a multi-donor finance facility to provide resources for climate change capacity building at national and local levels. Funding of the CCCA program is provided through a trust fund called the Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund (CCCA Trust Fund). Development partners are invited to make contributions to the fund in the form of pooled and non-targeted resources on basis of contractual agreements between each donor and UNDP. The legal status The CCCA Trust Fund is a multi-donor trust fund, which was established by the CCCA donors and government to apply a more coherent approach to climate change support for Cambodia. The Trust Fund is administered by UNDP and the operation of the trust fund is therefore implemented according to UNDP rules and procedures. The operational and administrative specificities of the framework for the CCCA Trust Fund are detailed in the CCCA Trust Fund Operational Manual. Each donor of the CCCA Trust Fund enters into a contractual agreement with UNDP for the administration of its funds. All donors have agreed on a program document and on a general Statement of Cooperation (SoC) to support Cambodia to address the challenges of Climate Change. The SoC details key principles of cooperation and harmonization that recognize the need to consult and cooperate in an open transparent manner in order to eliminate duplication of efforts, coordinate policies and procedures. 1 National funds selected for the case study analysis are: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation, China CMD Fund, Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund, Thailand Energy Conservation Promotion Fund, Lao Environmental Protection Fund, Micronesian Conservation Trust and Tuvalu Trust Fund.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "7eb89ae0-bb85-4649-9631-ade44900b6d7": {"__data__": {"id_": "7eb89ae0-bb85-4649-9631-ade44900b6d7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "26643c361d6269cc27bc49538021a336558f7fa57f47d79c58e011d761827218"}, "2": {"node_id": "af006a27-30a9-4a3e-91cd-53b2a6d1cb9c", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "90266d4a99df73d9d695d9a3579cda9932022ab8cef963451ea65fcbc8bd9c8a"}}, "hash": "ba0818363c1d86de579a7746901c409e1396611c0f810364b47efa1aad36adb2", "text": "http://www.snap-undp.org/elibrary/default.aspx 4 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund Donor contributions to the Trust Fund are pooled and not earmarked in anyway. The Trust Fund is open for additional contributions from new and existing donors. The organizational structure is based on government", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "9e96aa71-663c-47c3-8967-acb437ae92ef": {"__data__": {"id_": "9e96aa71-663c-47c3-8967-acb437ae92ef", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a7d67a293fd0432850c8c262e7900d8677322b27461a92afd9b541b4e58b90c0"}, "3": {"node_id": "e16cb2fe-e435-42b5-b25d-d1d84e65d6f7", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "5b2509f5be360e35375c044c23337d369a273ea2b2f4125d003c50b180d3d566"}}, "hash": "c7eec0e0390d3dc5601d144aa609362ae3900658454138f5f207053e1982b9a5", "text": "ownership and aligned with the existing government institutional arrangement. The Ministry of Environment, on behalf of the NCCC, is the government implementing partner (IP). A dedicated Trust Fund Secretariat is established at the Ministry of Environment to manage day-to-day operation of the Trust Fund. The Head of Secretariat is a government appointee and reports the progress of the CCCA program to the Programme Support Board (PSB). A Trust Fund Administrator, internationally recruited by UNDP, manages the Trust Fund, provides capacity development as well as financial assurance and reports on the utilization of the CCCA Fund to the government and donors. The CCCA programme also has a full-time international Technical Specialist Climate Change to provide substantive support and advice. The model of the CCCA Trust Fund The CCCA Trust Fund is a sinking fund, where all the funds committed will have been disbursed by the end of the agreed project timeframe. The initial design was for the duration of 3 years (2010-2012) and approximately US$ 8.9 million was committed for that period (Table 1). Recently the CCCA programme and thus its TF have been extended to 2014, with additional donor commitments being made (details to be finalized). Table 1. Committed funds to be managed by the CCCA Trust Fund Donors Committed 1 European Union EUR 2,205,816.06 2 DANIDA DKK 3,000,000.00 3 SIDA SEK 15,000,000.00 4 UNDP USD 3,000,000.00 Total USD 8,924,050.00 The CCCA is implemented through a series of grants that finance activities attempting to address Cambodia\u2019s climate change challenges. The CCCA program supports capacity building and institutional strengthening which are implemented by a grant facility. Initially grant components are focused on building resilience to climate change in coastal areas, and strengthening climate change awareness, and education as well as public information. Grants are provided to deliver five main outputs as agreed in the existing project document, including: \u2022 Result 1: Improved capacity to coordinate national policy making, capacity development, outreach/advocacy efforts, and to monitor the implementation of national climate change strategy, policy and plans. \u2022 Result 2: Improved access to updated climate change information, knowledge and learning opportunities at all levels. \u2022 Result 3: Strengthened capacity within the NCCC to mobilize and to effectively administer climate change funds and to prepare for a nationally owned trust fund. \u2022 Result 4: Increased resilience of coastal communities and ecosystems to climate change through adaptation planning, demonstrated targeted local interventions and provision of practical learning experience in adaptation planning to the NCCC. \u2022 Result 5: Strengthened capacity in government agencies and civil society organizations for developing and implementing climate change response initiatives in line with agreed national climate change priorities, independently or in partnerships, through access to new financial and technical resources. The grants approved by the Programme Support Board will be executed by relevant key line ministries, agencies and civil society organization, with technical support provided by international development partners as required. The grants provided for adaptation in coastal areas (Result 4) will be implemented by DHI Water Environment Health (formerly known as Danish Hydraulic Institute). In 2011, 5 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund 8 grants were approved and the contract between UNDP and DHI was signed for the Coastal Zone Project. The project expenditures as of December 2011 are presented in Table 2. Table 2. Expenditures as of December 2011 Activity Total project budget Cumulative Expenditure Balance Delivery (%) Result 1: National policy making 1,410,113 766,136 643,976 54% Result 2: Knowledge and learning platform 793,553 354,116 439,437 45% Result 3: Improved access to financial and technical resources 1,136,914 298,428 838,485 26% Result 4: Coastal Zone grant 2,256,000 463,100 1,792,900 21% Result 5: New Grants to Government and Civil Society Organisations 3,327,467 1,130,266 2,197,201 34% Total 8,924,049 3,012,048 5,912,001 34% Governing body and beneficiaries Policy decision making within the CCCA program is entrusted to a Programme Support Board (PSB). The PSB consists of eight members including four government representatives appointed by NCCC and four donor representatives.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e16cb2fe-e435-42b5-b25d-d1d84e65d6f7": {"__data__": {"id_": "e16cb2fe-e435-42b5-b25d-d1d84e65d6f7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "a7d67a293fd0432850c8c262e7900d8677322b27461a92afd9b541b4e58b90c0"}, "2": {"node_id": "9e96aa71-663c-47c3-8967-acb437ae92ef", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c7eec0e0390d3dc5601d144aa609362ae3900658454138f5f207053e1982b9a5"}}, "hash": "5b2509f5be360e35375c044c23337d369a273ea2b2f4125d003c50b180d3d566", "text": "The PSB meets at least twice a year to review and approve annual CCCA budgets and work plans and also to endorse or reject new recommended grant proposals. The decisions made during the PSB meetings are then submitted to the Trust Fund Secretariat to release funds in accordance with UNDP financial rules and regulations. The Fund Administrator and other relevant Development Partners (i.e. World Bank and the Asian Development Bank) can serve as observers in the PSB meetings. The inter-ministerial Climate Change Technical Team (CCTT) and short term independent individual experts provide technical support to the CCCA and advise the PSB on technical and programme issues. The CCTT was established", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "e536a1f8-52c7-47ce-83c9-6080ea0526fe": {"__data__": {"id_": "e536a1f8-52c7-47ce-83c9-6080ea0526fe", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c792984cd24d08d28a8fc2dcc003d9a52b8cbbcdc7c88e2b237077d0a2f0a8cc"}, "3": {"node_id": "fafdd062-a677-4ebd-bd17-c05f59daef10", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c74ac94aa75925f0ac1c22704bfdaa51efff03d710d2d205260b3002f6884aea"}}, "hash": "4e69998fa4c5b45b764e37177f8912d5f927a1219636bc3b9cd8166e67d8aae5", "text": "in 2011, mirroring the membership of NCCC, to provide technical support to the NCCC. The CCTT reviews and recommends to the PSB proposals for funding by the Trust Fund. The establishment of the CCTT is providing the necessary platform for policy discussions on climate change. Three CCTT meetings have been convened since its establishment and discussions took place covering a wide range of issues such as the CCTT ToR, Cambodia Climate Change Strategic Plan development, Trust Fund grants review, organization of the Second National Forum on Climate Change, review of the National Climate Change Information and Knowledge Management Strategy. The Trust Fund Secretariat, which is hosted by the Ministry of Environment (MoE), is responsible for day-to-day operation of the CCCA Trust Fund. The CCCA Trust Fund Secretariat is responsible to: \u2022 make necessary arrangements for the PSB meetings, including coordinating meeting dates among PSB members, preparing provisional meeting agenda and documents, issuing invitations and organizing technical-level preparation meetings; \u2022 provide administrative and logistics support to the PSB meetings such as making reservation of meeting rooms, preparing copies of required documents and arranging for simultaneous translation services; \u2022 keep meeting minutes, finalizing the official meeting minutes and archiving the meeting documents; \u2022 follow-up on implementation of PSB decisions with relevant parties. UNDP Country Office acts as the Trust Fund Manager for the CCCA Trust Fund in the interim period to ensure maximum accountability and transparency, with assurance provided by a dedicated Trust Fund Administrator (TFA), embedded in the Trust Fund Secretariat. 6 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund UNDP rules and procedures will be applied for the operation of the CCCA Trust Fund for the time UNDP acts as the Trust Fund Manager. The present is for three years but the Program is planned for a long-term commitment by the government and donors. The Management of the CCCA Trust Fund Project Cycle The CCCA Trust Fund finances climate change projects that respond to key priorities defined in the CCCA Programme Document, the National Strategic Development Plan (NSDP) Update 2009-2013, the National Adaptation Programme of Action to Climate Change (NAPA), and other relevant official documents. The Trust Fund Secretariat presents to the PSB, on an annual basis, resources required for grants in the form of Annual Work Plan, based on the funds available in the Trust Fund and the potential supplies and demands identified as well as the implementation capacity for the Trust Fund Secretariat. The CCCA Trust Fund applies \u2018\u2019calls for proposals\u2019\u2019 as a method of soliciting grant proposals from eligible parties. The Trust Fund Secretariat designs a call for proposals document and obtains an approval of the PSB on the scope and target amount before launching it in national newspapers. The Trust Fund Secretariat develops CCCA Grants Application Guidelines, which will inform the parties interested in accessing CCCA Trust Fund on specific requirements and conditions as per UNDP rules and regulations. The Guidelines also provides templates for preparing a concept note/full proposal. The Trust Fund Secretariat may design a call for proposals, which targets only a particular group of applicants (e.g. Government institutions only) or specific geographical area/priority sector depending on the demands.The maximum value of CCCA grants approved is US$300,000 per project (US$150,000 in case of NGO applicants). The CCCA Trust Fund, in principle, appraises grant proposals in two-step process: Concept Note and Full Project Proposal appraisals. \u2022 Concept Note Appraisal. Applicants are given 3-5 weeks (depending on the nature of the call) to prepare concept notes in accordance with the templates provided in the Grants Application Guidelines. Preparation time for concept note development may be adjusted depending on the capacities of targeted applicant groups or complexity of the call for proposals. Concept notes first undergo administrative screening by the Trust Fund Secretariat for eligibility compliance and documentation completeness. The Trust Fund Secretariat engages services of independent experts, on contract with UNDP, to conduct technical appraisal of concept notes that have passed the administrative screening, using the evaluation criteria provided by the Trust Fund Secretariat. Upon conclusion of expert appraisal, the Trust Fund Secretariat will convene the CCTT meeting where the independent expert representative will present results and findings from the technical appraisal to the CCTT members and issues are debated. The CCTT will prepare the recommendations on successful concept notes to the PSB.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "fafdd062-a677-4ebd-bd17-c05f59daef10": {"__data__": {"id_": "fafdd062-a677-4ebd-bd17-c05f59daef10", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "c792984cd24d08d28a8fc2dcc003d9a52b8cbbcdc7c88e2b237077d0a2f0a8cc"}, "2": {"node_id": "e536a1f8-52c7-47ce-83c9-6080ea0526fe", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "4e69998fa4c5b45b764e37177f8912d5f927a1219636bc3b9cd8166e67d8aae5"}}, "hash": "c74ac94aa75925f0ac1c22704bfdaa51efff03d710d2d205260b3002f6884aea", "text": "The CCTT will prepare the recommendations on successful concept notes to the PSB. The recommendations are signed by the CCTT Chair and by the Head of the Trust Fund Secretariat. The Trust Fund Secretariat will submit to the PSB a Concept Note Appraisal Report which describes the proceedings of the appraisal with the recommendations of the CCTT attached. PSB members will be requested", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "d3346e45-be4d-4d52-b56a-fc776d58becb": {"__data__": {"id_": "d3346e45-be4d-4d52-b56a-fc776d58becb", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "de9991772a4c55bf2ff1995a56dd46580d087cfa4cf375a6ac4ed7fde624bcb8"}}, "hash": "de9991772a4c55bf2ff1995a56dd46580d087cfa4cf375a6ac4ed7fde624bcb8", "text": "to provide their no-objection electronically. \u2022 Full Project Proposal Appraisal. Applicants whose concept notes have passed the technical appraisal shall be notified through a letter and invited to develop full project proposals in 6 weeks. Preparation time for full project proposal development may be adjusted depending on the capacities of targeted applicant groups or complexity of the call for proposals. All unsuccessful applicants will also receive notification letters including feedbacks on their concept notes. The Trust Fund Secretariat will organize a PSB meeting to take place shortly after the conclusion of appraisal process. Upon conclusion of technical appraisal, the Trust Fund Secretariat will prepare a Grant Submission Form to the PSB containing summary of project proposals and recommendations of the CCTT. The Trust Fund Secretariat will distribute to the PSB members the Grant Proposal Submission Form with project proposals attached one week prior to the date of the PSB meeting. 7 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund Based on the Letter of Agreement signed on 30 March 2011 between the MoE and UNDP, UNDP is allowed to disburse funds from the CCCA Trust Fund to grantees. UNDP will require a quarterly workplan and a fund request form from each grantee before disbursing the first installment. Templates for these forms will be provided to grantees as soon as the PSB makes decision on project proposals. UNDP will also conduct a brief capacity assessment of the grantees using UNDP standard checklists. Subsequent disbursement of funds is triggered by submission of quarterly report and workplan to the Trust Fund Secretariat, which will certify these documents and transmit them to UNDP to disburse the funds. Monitoring and Evaluation The CCCA Program with the Trust Fund Secretariat will be monitored in accordance with UNDP\u2019s rules and procedures, and in line with the provisions in the Statement of Cooperation among Development Partners. Monitoring progress will be based on the indicators in a log frame stated in the project document signed at the beginning of the program. The Head of the Trust Fund Secretariat will provide quarterly progress reports which after endorsement by the PSB is submitted to the Chair of the NCCC and the development partners. The Annual report will summarize the progress of implementation for the full year till December 31 and be sub mitted by the UNDP Country Office, following UNDP\u2019s quality assurance procedures to each partner donor. Grantees of the CCCA Trust Fund (Government agencies and civil society organizations) will submit quarterly narrative and financial progress reports to the TF Secretariat. These reports will be consolidated by the TF Secretariat and presented to the next PSB meeting, following UNDP quality assurance. A Joint Programme Review will take place annually. The purpose of the Joint Reviews is to assess progress and ensure that the program remains focused and in line with agreements between the government and development partners. The deliberations during the Annual Review will be based on the Annual Report. The Annual Review is concluded with formal minutes agreed between government and the development partners. Lessons learned The CCCA Trust Fund is one of the national climate funds that were established to pool external resources to finance climate actions in developing countries. Other similar trust funds for climate change include: Indonesia Climate Change Trust Fund (ICCTF), Bangladesh Climate Resilience Trust Fund and Bangladesh Climate Change Trust Fund. These funds were established as an immediate attempt to access climate finance to finance the implementation climate actions, therefore, their objectives focus mostly on pooling financial resources provided by development partners and channeling them to intended beneficiaries including government agencies, NGOs, universities and local communities. These funds are managed as sinking funds, where all committed funds should be disbursed within an agreed time frame. A sinking fund is relatively easy to set up especially when an international development partner will serve as the TF manager. However, impacts and outreach are likely limited because of the lack of innovative sources of funding tapped into, and the single financial instrument (grant modality) being applied. Therefore, the sustainability of the fund beyond the agreed project timeframe is in question. Especially for such sinking funds, it is important to realize their function in time and their limitations. Most of these newly established national climate funds assign multilateral agencies as the fund managers or administrators. The CCCA Trust Fund is administered by UNDP, which is similar to the ICCTF, while the World Bank is currently managing the Bangladesh Climate Resilience Trust Fund. Assigning multilateral agencies in managing the funds can be considered an immediate stepping-stone where a country can start receiving financial resources, which will be", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "f0d99abc-83b6-49a5-a18a-7949ccee7c85": {"__data__": {"id_": "f0d99abc-83b6-49a5-a18a-7949ccee7c85", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-cambodia-climate-change-alliance-trust-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "2192c57196532fb184148a0b21fdbf64394c54c8e3c4beb3868a3c2d1679e133"}}, "hash": "2192c57196532fb184148a0b21fdbf64394c54c8e3c4beb3868a3c2d1679e133", "text": "managed according to internationally accepted standards. At the same time, country public finance systems and capacity need to be further developed over time, which should result in a gradual increase in the use of country systems to access and manage international public climate finance. 8 Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund The CCCA Trust Fund, for instance, aims to develop the capacity of the government so that the management of the fund can be transferred to a country system after three years of the establishment. Transferring the management of a fund into a country system requires an agreed timeframe and a strong political commitment. The nationalization process of a trust fund can be learned from the Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation (BTFEC), a trust fund established to support conservation in Bhutan. The BTEFC was nationalized after five years of the establishment of the fund. This process was made possible because the Royal Charter, which governs the management of the fund, clearly instructed that the process of nationalization of the BTFEC should be completed in five years after the establishment. Authors: Silvia Irawan, Tin Ponlok, Kalyan Keo, Alex Heikens Cover Photo: Lien Heikens. Disclaimer: The views expressed in this publication are those of the authors and do not necessarily represent those of the United Nations, including UNDP, or its member states. Citation: Irawan et al. (2012) Case Study Report: Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund. A UNDP working paper. http://www.snap-undp.org/elibrary/default.aspx", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "cabb81b4-495c-4005-a843-77c4f323cdf1": {"__data__": {"id_": "cabb81b4-495c-4005-a843-77c4f323cdf1", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "33f9d53c380f875ebcb9e503694fe9a576f67f6aa7bb4631453b2bcfcc7dfe85"}, "3": {"node_id": "6fabc39d-403e-426c-a722-e62da5812e51", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "f0a364d400cdc88c0f47554f13e8fbc197fba73a12f7c9761ba5f10fb22ab5fe"}}, "hash": "1a2e86e66cdb5e3805fb7a407289e27a491507a7e89f6c5d2bfb4199bb13ac53", "text": "China Clean Development Mechanism Fund A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia National Climate Funds, jointly prepared Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund A case study providing inputs to discussions in Asia-Pacific region on the design and management of prepared by UNDP and the CCDMF. Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund Pacific region on the design and management of 2 Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund Table of Contents Introduction ................................................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 3 The design of the CCDMF at a glance ............................................................................................................................................................................................... 4 The role of the CCDMF in financing climate actions in China ............................................................................................................................................. 4 The legal status ...................................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 4 The model: a revolving fund ............................................................................................................................................................................................................ 5 Governing body and beneficiaries ................................................................................................................................................................................................ 6 The establishment process of the CCDMF ....................................................................................................................................................................................... 7 The management of the CCDMF ......................................................................................................................................................................................................... 8 Grant projects ........................................................................................................................................................................................................................................ 8 Investment projects ............................................................................................................................................................................................................................. 9 The monitoring and evaluation ...................................................................................................................................................................................................... 9 Lessons learned ........................................................................................................................................................................................................................................ 10 The role of the CCDMF in overall climate finance in China ................................................................................................................................................ 10 The source of capital ......................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 10 Innovative programs ......................................................................................................................................................................................................................... 10 3 Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund Introduction This paper aims to enrich knowledge sharing about the establishment and management of national climate funds (NCFs), which is organized by the Asia-Pacific Community of Practice on Climate Finance. To provide a technical input to the knowledge sharing, UNDP commissioned seven case studies on existing national funds in the fields of environment, conservation, energy, climate change and development. This paper reports the lessons learned extracted from the establishment and management of the China Clean Development Mechanism Fund (CCDMF), which is one of seven national funds across the Asia-Pacific region selected as a case study.1 The CCDMF is selected to provide an interesting case for countries in Asia-Pacific due to the following characteristics: 1. The role of the CCDMF within the overall climate finance architecture in China \u2013 As of the end of 2011, the CCDMF managed RMB 10 billion with the granting and investment portfolio of approximately RMB 285 million (US$ 4.5 million) and RMB 1.6 billion (US$ 253 million) respectively. Considering the amount of resources invested in energy efficiency, renewable energy and environmental protection by the Chinese central government (around RMB 170 billion in 2012),2the CCDMF should play a strategic role in overall climate finance in China to be of added value. The CCDMF is currently focusing on leveraging private sector engagement and supporting policy research and capacity building in addressing climate change in China. 2. The source of capital \u2013 The source of capital of the CCDMF, which is injected regularly by government levies collected from CDM projects, is a unique example of an innovative source of revenue for financing climate actions. The collection of the levies from CDM projects was mainly driven by the intention of the government to prevent industries from producing excessive HFC (to generate certified emission reductions), particularly considering the magnitude of CDM HFC-23 projects in China. The revenues collected are specifically earmarked to finance climate actions in the country. 3. Innovative programs funded by the CCDMF to leverage more resources - The revenue collected by the CCDMF is used mostly to finance investment programs to leverage additional resources from the private sector and to test out innovative financial and economic instruments to support actions to address climate change. Another endeavor is conducted together with commercial banks through a wealth management program to promote investment in energy efficiency and renewable energy. This report provides the summary of the overall design of the CCDMF and a short description about the process of the establishment and the management of the CCDMF. A brief analysis of the lessons learned from the establishment and management of the CCDMF are then presented. The case study analysis involved: literature review to set the scope of the study and in-depth interviews with relevant stakeholders: 1) the Fund Manager and Staff from the CCDMF, 2) board members: the Ministry of Finance (Deputy Director, International Financial Institution Division III), and the China Meteorological Administration, and 3) beneficiaries: the Energy Research Institute (affiliated to NDRC) and the Huafeng Group of Meteorological Audio & Video Information(affiliated to the China Meteorological Administration). Prior to finalization, the report has been reviewed by the CCDMF team and the UNDP China Country Office.", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "6fabc39d-403e-426c-a722-e62da5812e51": {"__data__": {"id_": "6fabc39d-403e-426c-a722-e62da5812e51", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "33f9d53c380f875ebcb9e503694fe9a576f67f6aa7bb4631453b2bcfcc7dfe85"}, "2": {"node_id": "cabb81b4-495c-4005-a843-77c4f323cdf1", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "1a2e86e66cdb5e3805fb7a407289e27a491507a7e89f6c5d2bfb4199bb13ac53"}}, "hash": "f0a364d400cdc88c0f47554f13e8fbc197fba73a12f7c9761ba5f10fb22ab5fe", "text": "1 National funds selected for the case study analysis are: Bhutan Trust Fund for Environmental Conservation, China CDM Fund, Cambodia Climate Change Alliance Trust Fund, Thailand Energy Conservation Promotion Fund, Lao Environmental Protection Fund, Micronesian Conservation Trust and Tuvalu Trust Fund. http://www.snap-undp.org/elibrary/default.aspx 2Source:http://www.gov.cn/gzdt/2012-05/24/content_2144823.htm 4 Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund The design of the CCDMF", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "feb2ca9f-c7a2-4d22-b9de-693ccba61754": {"__data__": {"id_": "feb2ca9f-c7a2-4d22-b9de-693ccba61754", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "53090919f402c6e4ac65489f0e5fe37be41b60eb10cc7c1916db22ba6167fed2"}}, "hash": "53090919f402c6e4ac65489f0e5fe37be41b60eb10cc7c1916db22ba6167fed2", "text": "at a glance The role of the CCDMF in financing climate actions in China The establishment of the CCDMF was driven by the characteristics of CDM projects in China. Of particular importance is the magnitude of CDM HFC-23 projects in China, hosting 11 out of 19 CDM HFC-23 projects worldwide. Certified Emission Reductions acquired by phasing out HFC-23, whose Global Warming Potential (GWP) is 11,700, are therefore significant. To avoid industries benefiting excessively from phasing out HFC-23, the government is applying levies to CDM HFC projects in China and also other types of CDM projects with a lesser extent. Channeling revenues collected from CDM projects through the traditional budget system would make it difficult to track the use of the revenues, as they would become part of the overall state budget. There were concerns that this could become subject to international criticism of using CDM projects to generate state revenues. The idea of the establishment of the CCDMF therefore came up following the meeting between Ministry of Finance, National Development and Reform Commission (NDRC), Ministry of Foreign Affairs, and Ministry of Science and Technology. Managing the revenues collected from CDM projects through the CCDMF is a way to ensure that the government allocates the collected levies to address climate change issues in the country. The CCDMF serves specific purposes in the overall climate finance architecture in China. The CCDMF specifically provides support for policy studies and leverage private sector contributions and investments in climate mitigation and adaptation projects in China. Three main strategic focuses of the CCDMF in supporting climate actions in China are: 1. Providing immediate supports for line ministries to conduct policy studies, international negotiation, capacity building and public awareness. The CCDMF provides specific support through its granting program for line ministries to carry out the aforementioned activities, which are considered as immediate actions to be implemented to address climate change. 2. Piloting innovative economic and financial instruments to reduce risks and remove market barriers in climate investments. The Ministry of Finance is then expected to allocate state budget to support the application of cost effective instruments that have been proven well functioning to address climate change at the national level. 3. Exploring and developing new models for bridging between public and private actors to leverage more capital support for China\u2019s efforts in combating and adapting to climate change. The fund positions itself as a policy institution that integrates government and market functions and pursues direct cooperation with business partners in the market to address issues of climate change. The legal status The CCDMF is a public institution that is affiliated with the Ministry of Finance. The CCDMF Management Center, which is running the day-to-day activities related to the collection, management and use of the CDM fund, is subject to the supervision of the Ministry of Finance. The Board of CCDMF is an interministerial body, which reviews the strategic planning and the regulation of the fund. (See discussion on the governing body of the CCDMF in detail in the next section). 5 Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund As a public fund, the CCDMF adopts market-oriented operation model and cooperates closely with companies and commercial financial institutions. As an innovative climate financing mechanism, the China CDM Fund will combine government fund, international assistance and social funding and serve as a platform for financing, action, cooperation and information gathering and exchange. The model: a revolving fund The CCDMF is a revolving fund that receives regular capital injection from levies collected by the government on CDM projects in China. Other possible sources of revenues are donations from international and domestic institutions, fiscal allocation and operating revenue of the fund. As of now, the revenues mostly come from the levies on CDM projects, which are totaling approximately RMB 10 Billion as of the end of 2011 from a total of 800 CDM projects currently receiving certified emission reductions (CERs). The rates of levies applied to CDM projects in China are: - 65 percent of levy on CER transfer benefit from HFC projects - 30 percent of levy on CER transfer benefit from nitrous oxide (N2O) projects related to adipic acid production - 10 percent of levy on CER transfer benefit from N2O projects related to the production of nitric acid - 5 percent of levy on CER transfer benefit from perfluorocarbons (PFC) projects - 2 percent of levy on CER transfer benefit from other CDM projects. To understand the composition of the revenue from the government levies of CDM projects, out of the total RMB 10 billion (US$ 1.5 billion) of the levies collected by the end", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "c8db6e77-51af-4db1-9e1d-b137afbe5eb7": {"__data__": {"id_": "c8db6e77-51af-4db1-9e1d-b137afbe5eb7", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "National Climate Fund Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "69b8c8a68f0a90dbc67677b10b88134ba2c718adf47c6e835a56bf24a0b7b3f2"}, "3": {"node_id": "7a23c53c-253a-4b64-8cac-d23721a8cd30", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/national-climate-fund-case-study-report-china-clean-development-mechanism-fund", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "6c4afb1528a9ac01d2e48b11bf3edb0ad190149c41359a1c18115a546271565d"}}, "hash": "eefbb86e34b68754d210fff67ab62d154e8ee7acd3a972ded5c931d7b8283b6c", "text": "of 2011, the HFC and the N2O projects made up the highest portion of the collected revenue, which was 89.2 percent and 9.3 percent respectively. The remaining CDM projects only contributed to around 1.5 percent to the overall revenue. Using a portion of the total revenues collected, the CCDMF implements investment projects to support industrial activities to pursue climate mitigation projects. The investment projects include approaches such as equity investment, entrusted loans, financing guarantees and other government-approved approaches. The return of the investments then allows the CCDMF to provide grants and finance climate-related efforts in China, particularly for line ministries dealing directly with the issues of climate change. Grant projects cannot be financed by the CCDMF main capital. Various programs currently implemented by the CCDMF can be summarized below (Figure 1): 1. Grant Projects \u2013 in 2008, the CCDMF launched its first 14 grant projects, totaling of RMB 25 million (US$ 3.9 million). The projects mainly focus on policy studies, research and public campaign on climate change. In 2011, another 125 grant projects were prepared for launching, with a total amount of RMB 260 million (US$ 41 million). The projects will formulate climate action plans and compilation of GHG inventories in all provinces in China as well as to develop carbon trade pilots in five provinces and others. 2. Investment projects \u2013 directly working with Chinese enterprises, as of the end of 2011, the CCDMF has provided concessional loans for 32 projects to reduce emissions in 14cities and provinces in China. From these projects, the CCDMF have leveraged RMB 9.5 billion (US$ 1.5 billion) from the total investment made by the CCDMF of RMB 1.6 billion (US$ 253 million). 3. Wealth Management \u2013 for the surplus capital, the CCDMF pursue risk-free wealth management such as making deposits in commercial banks. The CCDMF is not allowed to invest in stocks, stock-investing mutual funds, real estate, futures and other financial derivatives. Another form of wealth management activity pursued by the CCDMF is a contract-based cooperation model with commercial banks where it can leverage contributions from commercial banks for energy conservation and emission reduction projects. The CCDMF is working with the China Zheshang Bank and Industrial Bank respectively in the area of wealth management for clean development, which attract 100 percent additional commercial capital to support China\u2019s climate efforts. 6 Case Study Report: China Clean Development Mechanism Fund The CCDMF currently has a rough planning for the portion of financial resources allocated for grants, investments and those r cash. However, as the total resources managed by the CCDMF are increasing over ti between grants, investment and cash. In early 2011, the total revenue managed by the CCDMF was RMB 8 billion and the investme portfolio was 1.6 billion. This year, the total revenue is RMB 10 billion and wit investment portfolio. The CCDMF aims to allocate expect to use as much resources as possible for grant projects. discipline in the allocation of resources for grant projects to ensure sustainability Governing body and beneficiaries The China CDM Fund is governed by the Board of the China CDM Fund and the China CDM inter-ministerial body consisting of 7 line ministries responsible for climate actions in China: National Development and Reform Commission (NDRC), Ministry of Finance, Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Ministry of Scien Protection, Ministry of Agriculture and China Meteorological Administration. China, has been appointed by the State Council as the chair of the reviews the basic regulations as well as strategic planning of the fund, grant applications, annual budget plans, and financi The CCDMF Management Center, as a daily administrative body, i the guidance of the Board. Th